Indigenous peoples’ knowledge of the natural environment holds value for climate-change monitoring, adaptation, science and policy. The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) reports — often seen as definitive assessments of climate science — risk marginalizing Indigenous Knowledges because of a lack of inclusion of Indigenous writers and reviewers (J. D. Ford et al. Nature Clim. Change 6, 349–353; 2016). These assessments must include Indigenous voices.

